COMPARATIVE ANALYSIS FOR HEART DISEASE PREDICTION¶

Objective¶

We aim to find the model that best predicts heart disease risk so that it can be used to screen for the disease in high-risk populations.

#Naming the axis
CategoricalV_axis_name = ["Gender", "Chest Pain", "Blood sugar", "Resting Electrocardiographic",
                      "Exercise Induced Angina", "Slope of ST Segment", "Major Vessels", "Thal", "Target"]

#Pie charts for categorical variables
for i, z in list(zip(CategoricalV, CategoricalV_axis_name)):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (8, 6))
    
    observed_value = list(data[i].value_counts().index)
    Total_value = list(data[i].value_counts())
    
    ax.pie(Total_value, labels= observed_value, autopct = '%1.1f%%', startangle = 110, labeldistance = 1.1)
    ax.axis("equal") 
    
    plt.title((i + "(" + z + ")")) 
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

The results shows that

  • 68.3% of the patients are male and 31.7% are female.

  • 54.5% have a heart attack risk and the remaining 45.5% have no heart attack risk.

new_data = data

#Converting some variables to categorical variables
new_data['sex'] = new_data['sex'].astype('category')
new_data['cp'] = new_data['cp'].astype('category')
new_data['fbs'] = new_data['fbs'].astype('category')
new_data['restecg'] = new_data['restecg'].astype('category')
new_data['exng'] = new_data['exng'].astype('category')
new_data['slp'] = new_data['slp'].astype('category')
new_data['caa'] = new_data['caa'].astype('category')
new_data['thall'] = new_data['thall'].astype('category')
new_data['output'] = new_data['output'].astype('category')

Splitting the dataset into training and test data¶

In [47]:
#defining 'X' and 'Y'
Y = new_data['output']
X = new_data.drop('output', axis = 1 , inplace = False)

#Scaling The Data
X = preprocessing.StandardScaler().fit(X).transform(X.astype(float))

#splitting the data
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size = 0.3, random_state = 4)

CLASSIFICATION¶

In this section I will use 3 classification methods, namely: K-means Algorithm, Logistic regression, Support vector machines (SVM).

1. K-means Algorithm¶

In [48]:
#Calculating the number of k using codes
shubh = []
for i in range(1,10):
  kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = i, init = 'k-means++', max_iter = 1001, n_init = 9, random_state = 4)
  kmeans.fit(x_train)
  shubh.append(kmeans.inertia_)

knee_loc = KneeLocator(range(1, 10),shubh, curve="convex", direction="decreasing")
knee_loc.elbow
Out[48]:
4
In [49]:
#Create KNN Classifier
Knn_model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=4)

#Train the model 
Knn_model.fit(x_train, y_train)

#Predict the response
Y_PredKnn_model = Knn_model.predict(x_test)

#Evaluation
print("The Accuracy of the knn model is:",metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, Y_PredKnn_model))

The Accuracy of the knn model is: 0.7142857142857143

2. Logistic regression¶

In [50]:
logistic_model = LogisticRegression()
# fitting the model
logistic_model.fit(x_train,y_train)

#prediction
y_pred=logistic_model.predict(x_test)

#Evaluation
print("The Accuracy of the logistic regression model is:",metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))

The Accuracy of the logistic regression model is: 0.8021978021978022

3. Support Vector Machine¶

In [51]:
svm_model = svm.SVC(kernel='linear') # Linear Kernel
#Train the model 
svm_model.fit(x_train, y_train)

#Prediction 
y_predictSVM = svm_model.predict(x_test)

print("The Accuracy of the support vector machine model is:",metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_predictSVM))

The Accuracy of the support vector machine model is: 0.7912087912087912
  • Therefore the best performing was Logistic regression model, which had an accuracy score of 0.8021978021978022.
